title: For Sale/Trade:  1911 Smith & Wesson Model Military & Police, .38 Special, Nickel Finish.
postcontent:
I have a 1911 Smith & Wesson Model Military & Police in .38 Special. It has its ORIGINAL nickel finish and a 4-inch tapered barrel. Everything about the gun is ORIGINAL , including the grips. As far as condition goes, I would say it's overall it's in excellent (95%). There is some very slight pitting on a few parts of the nickel finish, but otherwise, the gun is perfect. The grips are flawless, including the medallions. Further, the inside of the cylinders are also excellent, as is the inside of the barrel, the extractor rod, the forcing cone, the hammer, the firing pin, the cylinder release latch, and the trigger. There is no carbon buildup in the either the cylinders or the barrel, nor amy piiting or rust. The rifling in the barrel is perfect, with no pitting or any visible wear. The action is butter smooth, and the trigger is very crisp. The gun is TIGHT. There is absolutely no play in the cylinder during lockup, whether in double or single action. I'd say the nickel is about 90%-95%, but the rest of the gun is 98%. Truly amazing for a gun 104 years old. The serial number starts with 198. I called Smith & Wesson and they dated the gun as being a late 1911 model. This means the gun is older than the Titanic.

I've also had it checked by a gunsmith, and he marvelled at how tight it was. We even shot it a few times (one cylinder worth of ammo). It's very, very accurate.

My asking price for this gem (nickel guns in this model are quite rare) is $650. This is a very, very good price, as the most current 2015 Blue Book of Gun Values (the best source available) puts the value of this gun at anywhere from $850-$1225 in this condition, or even any grade close to this condition. In addition, I also have some new Winchester ammo (box of 50, 125 grain jacketed hollow point) that I will throw in, along with a nice leather holster that fits the gun perfectly. This gun is a STEAL for any Smith & Wesson collector.

This gun is 104 years old, and looks almost brand new. It's beautiful. Plus, it's a true collectors piece. It's outright strange that I haven't gotten any offers on this gun at this price.

I can be reached at REDACTED or at REDACTED. Kentucky residents over 21 only. Cash only. I am willing to drive to meet someone at a reasonable distance from Owensboro. I would also consider a trade for a Smith & Wesson Model 57, Model 657, Model 66, or Model 19.
